386→                        <div id="content">A positive odd integer $m$ such that none of $2^km+1$ are prime for $k\geq 0$ is called a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sierpi%C5%84ski_number" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">Sierpinski number</a>. We say that a set of primes $P$ is a covering set for $m$ if every $2^km+1$ is divisible by some $p\in P$.<br><br>Are there Sierpinski numbers with no finite covering set of primes?</div>
387→                        <div id="problem_id"><a href="/1113">#1113</a>: <a href="#cite-ErGr80-1113" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ErGr80','1113'); return false;">[ErGr80,p.27]</a></div>
